full_text:
Not to mention that when they want to &quot;test&quot; something they are already skeptical about, then they will come up with impossible criteria. The day I finally stopped caring why a ghost box worked and just accepted that it did was the start of rewarding sessions. 

I think most of us are beyond the point where skeptics can make a dent in our searching for answers. Skepticism can be good, but sometimes it can be self defeating. More people just want to make a name for themselves by trying to be the one that brought down this or that device. If they would try some of these methods with an open mind and a brief suspension of disbelief, then they might get their own rewarding experiences as well...

Andy

